review_blob: 64oz growler fresh from the brewery. Pours a hazy amber/orange. Plenty of foamy head that takes some time to subside and leaves just about the perfect amount on top. Aroma of pineapples, citrus, and tropical fruit. Big taste to this one. Beutifally balanced malts and hops. Rye really shines through in a fiery way. Hops come through a few seconds later. Palate is left with just the right amount of biterness for this type of beer. An absolutely wonderful brew. Hits all of my marks. May as well scrap regular rye guy and brew this. Its much bolder, and the flavor shines through much better. Great work as always!
beer_name: Beyond the Pale Imperial Rye Guy

review_blob: Bomber from the LCBO. Pours a hazy blonde/copper colour. thick head that quickly turned a bit smaller and creamy. Wonderful nose - tropical fruits like guava and pineapple, marmalade and orange, a little bit of pine resin. I honestly cant stop smelling this stuff. Wonderful taste - guava and mandarin orange. Bitterness is just right for a standard, yet adventurous, IPA. Tart citrus flavour shines through on the palate. A wonderful example of a standard single IPA. Hop complexity really shines through without destroying your palate. .
beer_name: Great Lakes Brewing THRUST! An IPA

review_blob: 355ml can brought to me from Florida. Pours a deep, mahogany brown with a full and aggressive head. Nose is weak, but has some chocolate, roasted malts, and caramel. Taste is caramel, toffee, roasted malts, wood. Almost tastes barrel aged. Clean palate with little aftertaste, but enough to remind you how great it was. A wonderful example of a brown ale. Im very impressed with this one, and cant wait to get my hands on more of Cigar Citys offerings.

12 fl. oz. bottle brought to me from Florida. Pours like the standard Corona type mexican cerveza, which is light straw coloured with a fair amount of head that is quickly gone. Aroma of grains and agave; interesting, but not great. Tastes like a cheap mexican lager with agave in it. Weird. Almost tastes artificial. Clean palate. Not my taste at all. More of an interesting novelty.

355ml can brought to me from Florida. Pours a clear orange/yellow with a thick off white head. Aroma is...coconut. It literally smells like a freshly cracked coconut. Taste is...coconut. Nothing but coconut. If there is a beer in here, I cant find it. And a coconut after taste...imagine that. Its an interesting beer, and would likely best be enjoyed on a hot day at the beach. I think it could be improved by giving a bit more of a malt backbone for the coconut to grow on. Not really my style, but good.
beer_name: Miami Brewing Big Rod Coconut Ale

review_blob: 355ml can brought to me from Florida. Pours a very pale, slightly cloudy, yellow. Little to no head to speak of. Not much aroma, maybe a little bit of grain. Good mouth feel, carbonation is bang on for this style. Taste is grains, bread, maybe a little butter. Slight floral hop presence. Very clean on the palate. A fantastic example of this style.
beer_name: Bold City Killer Whale Cream Ale

review_blob: 355ml can brought to me from Florida. Pours a very clear orange colour, a few small bits floating around. Nice aroma, but not great - slightly astringent, maybe some citrus. I really like the taste. A semi-hop forward APA. Nice malt backbone, grassy and citrus hop profile. Almost a slightly swampy taste, but in a good way. I really enjoyed this brew. Goes down dangerously easily. Would be fantastic for a day on the lake. I really like the can design, too. Well done.
beer_name: Swamp Head Stump Knocker Pale Ale

review_blob: 64oz. Growler. Pours amber with a slightly coppery tone. Lots of head initially, but quickly subsided. Pine, citrus, pineapple, and juicy fruit gum on the nose. Hop taste is right in your face. Smacks your taste buds. I can taste some sweeter malts, but they are overpowered by the hops. Excellent for this style. Very flavourful. The 8.2% ABV i well hidden. This one is dangerous... I agree with the other reviewers that say let it warm up a bit. It mellows the taste a bit. Good mouth feel. I initially thought the carbonation was a bit high, but it subsided relatively quickly.

473ml can from LCBO. Pours a hazy orange with some sediment. Very thin and foamy head, almost light and airy. Nose is citrus, pine, and fresh hops. Maybe some tropical fruit. Tastes of pine, grapefruit, and some sweeter malts. Bitterness hits you in the back of the tongue. Resinous, yet light. Hops are not quite balanced by the malts, but typical for the West Coast IPA style. A stellar brew. For sure on my top 10 IPA list. Rivals some of the IPAs from my local brewers. Would love an imperial version. Sawdust City has been turning out some amazing brews. Perhaps a summer trip to Gravenhurst is in the cards... Very well done.

Tallboy from the LCBO. Pours black. Jet black. As black as space itself. Like a thick oil. Medium head, retains a nice lacing. Nose is slightly astringent. Maybe piney. Flavour is...wow. Incredible. Deep roasted caramel, dark chocolate, herbs, pine. Wow. Hides the 10%+ ABV well. Very well balanced. A little too much hop presence for a stout, in my opinion, but balances well with the malts and alcohol. Beautiful mouth feel. Slick and almost oily. Carbonation is just right.
beer_name: Sawdust City Long, Dark Voyage to Uranus

review_blob: Bomber from the LCBO. Pours fairly dark. Slight reddish tinge. Lots of head initially, but quickly disappeared.Aroma is caramel, smoke, smoked meat. Bacon is certainly present in the nose, but that?s where it ends. Flavour is that of burnt caramel, roasted barley, some sweeter malts. No bacon to speak of. Smoke is not as pronounced as I would have thought, either. A little on the thin side for a stout, in my opinion and a little too carbonated for my taste, but not bad. Clean aftertaste, nothing really left on my palate except a bit of bitterness. It?s good, but I was expecting more from this beer.

32oz growler from the brewery. Pours a dark, hazy orange. Almost thick. Thin lacing of head that disappears fairly quick. Aroma of pine, citrus, tropical fruit. Super hoppy taste. Again, pine and tropical fruits, but balanced well by the malts. Sort of a burnt caramel undertone. Bitter aftertaste, but at 90 IBU, expected. Very nice. Not for for the faint of heart, though.
beer_name: Beyond the Pale Imperial Super Guy

review_blob: Growler from the brewery. Pours a very light golden colour. Foamy white head with some retention. Not much taste at all.  Cereals and bread are the main notes I pick out.  Boring and bland overall. Maybe good for those that don?t really like beer. Have to admit, I was pretty disappointed with this one.

Colour is dark reddish / brown. The taste is that of toasted malt, a bit of cocoa, maybe a bit of something spicy. Really nailed the fine carbonation, good overall mouth feel. Leaves my palate with a bit of...something I cant quite put my finger on, which is why I cant rate it higher. Nonetheless; a good porter, overall.
beer_name: Brasseurs du Monde Gamme Passion Big Ben Porter
